Description: Cypriot terracotta figure of dog. Handmade dog in primitive style. Pale buff fabric with fine black inclusions.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Temple of Aphrodite (Naukratis), Context Φ16 or 17
Curator's comments: Dogs are rarely depicted in Cypriot art until the 6th century BC, when they become very common in coroplastic art (Karageorghis 1996, 42). Closest parallels from Cyprus and specifically at Salamis-Cellarka are dated to the 6th century BC and the Cypro-Archaic II period (Karageorghis 1996, 42-5, pls 25.9,11, 26.4 Types O10-O11 & O16). 'c' written on left shoulder in pencil by excavators? ‘From a 26th Dynasty context’ along with 1911,0710.92-106 (Bailey 2008, 186). Found with other figures marked "T ΑΦ16" or "T ΑΦ17" (Temple of Aphrodite context 16 or 17). Karageorghis, V. 1996. The coroplastic art of ancient Cyprus. VI. The Cypro-Archaic Period monsters, animals and miscellanea. Nicosia, University of Cyprus.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (DA.086) (Phase 1)
